{{more footnotes|date=February 2013}}
The act of swallowing live [[goldfish]] was an American school [[Fad|trend]] popularized in the late 1930s.<ref>http://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/2011/01/1939-the-year-of-goldfish-swallowing.html</ref>
==History== Although it is not clear how the fad emerged, various people have made claims. A 1963 letter to the ''New York Times'' claimed that it was started by a man named Lothrop Withington Jr., who was a freshman at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] University and supposedly did so as part of a bid to become class president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/2011/01/1939-the-year-of-goldfish-swallowing.html|title=1939: The year of goldfish gulping|website=National Museum of American History|language=en|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ripleys.com/weird-news/goldfish-swallowing/|title=College Bros in the 1930s Were the Champs of Goldfish Swallowing|date=2018-02-13|work=Ripley's Believe It or Not!|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en-US}}</ref> The stunt started a competition between multiple universities such as Penn State, MIT, and Harvard in an attempt to surpass one another.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/great-goldfish-swallowing-craze-1939-180954429/|title=The Great Goldfish Swallowing Craze of 1939 Never Really Ended|last=Clark|first=Laura|work=Smithsonian|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> Women also took part in the trend, as in April 1939 Marie Hensen from the University of Missouri was recorded{{By whom|date=May 2018}} as the first woman to swallow a goldfish.<ref name=":1" />
Although once widely practiced, the stunt is rare today, but has made appearances in recent entertainment. In 2000, ''Jackass'' star Steve-O swallowed a live goldfish, only to vomit it moments later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/future-proof/2014/02/how-long-can-goldfish-survive-if-you-swallow-it|title=How long can a goldfish survive if you swallow it?|last=|first=|date=|website=NewStatesman|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-21}}</ref>
Another possibility in the origins of goldfish swallowing comes from Chicago bartenders, most notably Matt Schulien (who performed magic while tending bar at his family's restaurant), who would cut up carrots to look like goldfish tails. When performing the stunt, bartenders would reach into a bowl of goldfish kept behind the bar while palming the carrot piece, placing that in between their pursed lips, using their tongues to lever it up and down to mimic the actions of a live fish, finally swallowing the carrot piece. The trick dates back to the 1920s, and some people believe that the fad could have been started by college students fooled by the trick.{{Citation needed|date=March 2018}}
According to the National Museum of American History, goldfish swallowing was such a craze at universities during the early 20th century that it made appearances in several news publications, including the ''New York Times'' and the ''Washington Post''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/2011/01/1939-the-year-of-goldfish-swallowing.html|title=1939: the year of goldfish swallowing|publisher=Smithsonian|accessdate=28 March 2018}}</ref>
== Legislation == The stunt became so popular that Massachusetts State Senator George Krapf filed a bill to "preserve the fish from cruel and wanton consumption."<ref>{{cite news |first=Richard A. |last=Burgheim |url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/1952/5/6/goldfish-swallowing-college-fad-started-here/?page=single |work=[[The Harvard Crimson]] |title=Goldfish Swallowing: College Fad Started Here, Spread Over World |date=6 May 1952 |access-date=27 May 2018}}</ref>
